## EXECUTION RULES

**RULE #1 — Execute everything yourself. Never list commands for the user to run.**

**RULE #2 — Fix loop: if a command fails -> read the error -> fix -> re-run. Max 3 attempts.
If the error persists, report it with full analysis and stop.**

**RULE #3 — Verify project state BEFORE starting any task:**
```bash
# Migration state
cd waas/apps/api && python -m alembic current

# TypeScript errors (must be 0)
cd waas/apps/admin && npx tsc --noEmit 2>&1 | wc -l

# Container status
docker compose -f waas/docker-compose.yml ps

# Recent container logs (check for pre-existing errors)
docker compose -f waas/docker-compose.yml logs api   --tail=30 --no-log-prefix 2>&1
docker compose -f waas/docker-compose.yml logs admin --tail=30 --no-log-prefix 2>&1
```

**RULE #4 — Never modify existing migrations 001-017. Always create new ones.**

**RULE #5 — Tenant isolation is SACRED. Every query must include WHERE tenant_id = X.**

**RULE #6 — Every user-visible string in the frontend uses t('key'). Never hardcoded.**
Always add translations to all three files: en.json, pt.json, es.json.

**RULE #7 — Shared components: grep all usages before modifying.**
New props must always be optional with defaults. Never remove existing props.

**RULE #8 — The environment is running. After any restart or deploy, ALWAYS verify logs.**
```bash
# Apply migration
cd waas/apps/api && python -m alembic upgrade head

# Restart and mandatory log verification
docker compose -f waas/docker-compose.yml restart api admin
sleep 8
docker compose -f waas/docker-compose.yml ps

# MANDATORY: read logs after restart — look for ERROR, CRITICAL, Traceback
docker compose -f waas/docker-compose.yml logs api   --tail=60 --no-log-prefix 2>&1
docker compose -f waas/docker-compose.yml logs admin --tail=60 --no-log-prefix 2>&1

# If ERROR or Traceback found in logs -> fix before proceeding
```

**RULE #9 — FORBIDDEN phrases (never write these):**
- "If you want, in the next step..."
- "I can implement this if you'd like."
- "As a next step, I suggest..."
- "You can now run..."
- "Remember to configure..."
- "Feel free to test..."

**RULE #10 — Canonical design system (waas-panel.html). See DESIGN SYSTEM in waas-design-db-auth-templates.mdc.**
Use only SVG inline or lucide-react for icons. Emojis are forbidden in any interface element.

**RULE #11 — Cognitive complexity: no file may exceed 300 lines.**
This rule applies to the entire project: backend, frontend, tests, and config.

When creating a new file:
- Plan the split before writing
- If a file would naturally exceed 300 lines -> split into smaller modules first

When editing an existing file at 250+ lines:
- Refactor before adding code
- Extract functions/classes to separate files until it fits within 300 lines
- Only then add the new functionality

How to split each file type:

- **FastAPI Router > 300 lines:** Split by resource (e.g. reviews_list.py + reviews_detail.py) or by responsibility (reviews_public.py + reviews_admin.py). Register all in main.py.
- **Repository > 300 lines:** name_repository.py (base CRUD) + name_queries.py (filters/aggregations).
- **Schema > 300 lines:** name_schema_input.py (Create/Update) + name_schema_output.py (Response/List).
- **.tsx page > 300 lines:** Extract to components/MODULE/ComponentName.tsx; page orchestrates, components render.
- **Service > 300 lines:** Split by responsibility (e.g. provisioning_steps.py + provisioning_service.py).

After any implementation, verify:
```bash
find waas/apps -name "*.py" -o -name "*.tsx" -o -name "*.ts" | xargs wc -l 2>/dev/null | sort -rn | head -20
```
If any file in the newly created module exceeds 300 lines -> refactor before delivering.
Include in the final report: top 5 largest files of the module with line counts.

